            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "I think I'm starting to piece an understanding of this. It seems that when creating the split, SIGWINCH is sent to bash, and this makes readline decide to clear the command line with a `\\r\\33[K\\r\\33[A\\33[K\\r` (IIUC, these are Carriage Return, CSI K, Carriage Return, CSI A and CSI K, with CSI K meaning clear everything on the right of the cursor and CSI A meaning go one line up) before redrawing it. If this happens while libvterm/neovim is still reacting to the resize (e.g. synchronizing the contents of libvterm's buffers with the underlying buffer), things go wrong.\r\n\r\nI haven't tried, and I'm far from certain of it, but the solution might be to perform the synchronization of libvterm's buffer and of neovim's buffer through libvterm's `resize` callback, instead of performing it after having called libvterm's `set_size`.",
